It is an individual work.
I also created a webpage for this work
https://nisawooo.github.io/Big-data-individual-assignment/ 


1. What This Project Is

An end-to-end AI project plan proposing a clinical NLP proof-of-concept for Tempus AI, a US precision medicine company with 40 million patient records-78% of which remain locked in unstructured free text. The PoC designs a pipeline to automatically extract and structure Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus data from GP free-text notes, grounded in the Irish healthcare context and GDPR constraints.



2. What I Built

Business case rooted in real Irish healthcare data (€601M annual diabetes inpatient cost, HSE eHealth maturity at 25% vs EU average 83%)
China–Ireland comparative analysis using peer-reviewed literature on Ningbo's regional health platform (Li et al., 2020) as a proof of feasibility before arguing why the approach requires re-engineering for GDPR
Three everyday analogies (parcel sorting → NER, currency exchange → OMOP CDM, airport security → confidence scoring) to make NLP architecture accessible without sacrificing technical precision
7-stage pipeline: Kafka ingestion → Presidio PHI de-identification → ClinicalBERT NER → confidence routing → OMOP CDM v5.4 harmonisation → Gold serving → MLflow audit logging
Model selection rationale: ClinicalBERT over GPT-4, with honest critique of domain mismatch risk on GP text vs hospital discharge notes
Financial model: 5-year cashflow with explicit costs, Insights licensing revenue projections, break-even at ~12 months, ROI ~19.5× — all figures annotated as illustrative, not audited
ESG analysis across E, S, G dimensions with a section explicitly acknowledging the commercial maximisation vs GDPR minimisation tension rather than glossing over it



3. What I Learned

How to design a clinical AI project plan that satisfies commercial, regulatory, and clinical stakeholder requirements simultaneously — not just the technical architecture
The practical difference between HIPAA and GDPR in AI deployment: right to erasure, data minimisation, and lawful basis for processing are not HIPAA concepts and require different pipeline design decisions
Why confidence thresholds, human-in-the-loop queues, and active learning are governance mechanisms as much as performance mechanisms
How to use a comparative international case (China) honestly, as a proof of feasibility rather than a direct template, and argue what needs to change before the approach transfers
